<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>DT-466E and 530E Diesel Engine Service (1995 through 1999) - SECTION 4: CYLINDER HEAD AND VALVES - CYLINDER
        HEAD RECONDITIONING - VALVE SPRINGS
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="clean" graphiccount="4">
        <title>VALVE SPRINGS</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Cleaning</title>
            <para>Clean all valve springs and seats in a suitable solvent.</para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Inspection</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Visually inspect valve springs for rust, pitting and cracks. Look for spring
                    distortion.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Spring ends must be flat and square to prevent lateral loads on valve stem. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600458">4.58</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Out of square springs place a side load on the stem causing rapid guide wear.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="ef1600457" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg5194" filename="../figeg5/eg5194.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.57 Installing Valve Seat Inserts</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">1. Valve Seat Insert</callout1>
                        <callout1 type="arabic">2. Installation Tool</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1600458" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg5201" filename="../figeg5/eg5201.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4.58 Checking Valve Springs</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Measure valve spring tension using valve spring tester
                    <emph type="bold">ZTSE2241</emph>. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600459">4.59</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    and "
                    <emph type="bold">SPECIFICATIONS"</emph>.
                </para>
                <para>Measure maximum spring length in use (valve closed).</para>
                <para>Measure minimum length in use (valve open).</para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Apply the appropriate test load to each spring and determine if test length is achieved.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Replace any valve spring which is rusted, pitted, cracked, bent or incapable of meeting
                    tension requirements.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Valve Rotators</title>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">CLEANING</emph>
            </para>
            <para>Clean rotators in a clean solvent.</para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">INSPECTION</emph>
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">To properly test the rotator for function, a valve spring load must be applied to the
                    rotator.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>THE ROTATOR MUST BE LUBRICATED WITH CLEAN ENGINE OIL PRIOR TO TESTING.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Place the valve spring with the rotator in the spring tester
                    <emph type="bold">ZTSE2241</emph>. Place a ball bearing between the rotator and ram of the spring
                    tester. The ball bearing must be large enough to prevent ram from touching any part of the rotator.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Paint a reference line on the rotator.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Compress the valve spring rapidly with even pressure and observe the rotator as it turns
                    (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600460">4.60</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Replace any rotator which does
                    <emph type="bold">NOT</emph>
                    turn.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Valve Spring Locks</title>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">CLEANING</emph>
            </para>
            <para>Clean valve spring locks in a suitable solvent.</para>
            <para>
                <emph type="bold">INSPECTION</emph>
            </para>
            <para>Visually inspect inside and outside of the valve spring locks for wear. Replace any worn spring locks,
                as required.
            </para>
            <figure id="ef1600459" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="eg5202" filename="../figeg5/eg5202.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
                <caption>Figure 4.59 Checking Valve Spring Tension</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="ef1600460" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="eg5206" filename="../figeg5/eg5206.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
                <caption>Figure 4.60 Checking Valve Rotator</caption>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
